data.content:
Here's what happened and how to fix it:

## The Problem: C# 14 Span Overload Resolution

In C# 14, `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` participate in overload resolution more broadly. When you write `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, the compiler now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (a span-based method) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**.

`MemoryExtensions.Contains` cannot be represented in a LINQ expression tree, so it throws at runtime — expression trees don't support span-based methods.

## The Fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>`, use `.AsEnumerable()`, or call the static method explicitly:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these forces the compiler to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains`, which is expression-tree-compatible. The same issue applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays (now binds to in-place `MemoryExtensions.Reverse`).
